data.content:
Yes — you can use **tuples** with `DynamicData` to get type safety and avoid the `object[]` casting:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What's better:**
- **Type safety** — compiler catches mismatched types instead of runtime failures
- **Named members** — self-documenting test data
- **No casting** — MSTest 3.x+ unpacks tuples into method parameters automatically

> Requires **MSTest 3.8+**. If you're on an older version, `[DataRow]` is the simpler alternative for constant values like these:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

Use `DynamicData` with tuples when your test data involves non-constants (computed values, objects). Use `[DataRow]` when all values are compile-time constants.
